sophy of freedom is a construction of modern, Western masculinity. Reason, which alone can make freedom possible, subverts and orders chaotic nature and protects the rational subject from the enervating influences of the senses and the imagination. The feminized, sexually charged Orient is a threat to the historical achievement of Western male rationality. Germana's book emphasizes aesthetics in the German orientalist discourse, a subject that has received little attention todate. In this tradition of German thought, aesthetics became a form of spiritual anthropology, ordering and classifying societies, races, and genders in terms of their ability to master the senses and the imagination, forces thatundermine rational autonomy, the very source of human (i.e., masculine) dignity. Nicholas A. Germana is Professor of History at Keene State College, New Hampshire.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEast and WestxHistory. 0aGerman philosophy. 0aOrientalismzGermanyxHistory. 0aPhilosophy, German. 4aGerman Literature. 4aModern History. 4aPhilosophy. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh  aAsia.  aColonialism.  aCulture.  aEuropean History.  aFeminine.  aFeminism.  aGender.  aGerman History.  aGermany.  aImmanuel Kant.  aMasculinity.  aModern History.  aNineteenth Century.  aOrient.  aOrientalism.  aOther.  aPhilosophy.  aPolitics.  aSexuality.  aWestern culture.  apost-Kantian.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311143130740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781787440609?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787440609423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787440609/original  a978-3-11-143130-7  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles